{"parse":{"title":"sugar","pageid":8414,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Sugar|sugár}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|shugar||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|id=sugar sugar|:inh|enm:sugre|tree=1|text=++}} Akin to {{cog|grc|κρόκη||pebble}}, whence the words {{m|en|crocodile}} and {{m|en|krokodil}} are derived. {{doublet|en|jaggery|sucro-}}.\n\nThe verb is from {{inh|en|enm|sugren}}, from the noun.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=v|id=3597292738}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈʃʊɡə/|a=RP,AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈʃɵɡə/|a=SSB}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-sugar.ogg|a=UK|IPA=[ˈʃɵɡə]}}\n* {{enPR|sho͝ogʹər|a=GA,CA}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈʃʊɡɚ/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-sugar.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈʃʉɡəɾ/|a=Scotland}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈʃʉɡəɹ/|a=NI}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʊɡə(ɹ)|s=2}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A food consisting of small, sweet crystals, principally of [[sucrose]], obtained from [[sugar cane]] or [[sugar beet]] and used as [[sweetener]] and [[preservative]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The universal cook: and city and country housekeeper|author=Francis Collingwood|year=1792|passage=To a pound of gooseberries take a pound and a half of double-refined '''sugar'''. Clarify the '''sugar''' with water, a pint to a pound of '''sugar''', and when the syrup is cold, put the gooseberries single in your preserving pan, put the syrup to them, and set them on a gentle fire.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xJMEAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22sugar%22&pg=PA279#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Sugar Cane|volume=27|page=171|passage=There appears to be no prospect of success in attempting to combat the crisis by international arrangement, and any improvement in '''sugar''' prices can only be looked for from a diminution of the production, either as a consequence of deficient crops, or of a reduction in manufacture.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8UpNAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22sugar%20prices%22&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%20prices%22&f=false|date=April 1 1895|issue=309|title=The Present Crisis}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Food Politics: What Everyone Needs to Know?|author=Robert Paarlberg|year=2013|passage=Even in extreme cases such as chemical pollution in the Florida Everglades from heavily subsidized '''sugar''' farming, strong regulations are routinely blocked by industry.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AcQ7AAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT109&dq=%22sugar%20farming%22&pg=PT109#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%20farming%22&f=false}}\n# {{lb|en|countable}} Any specific variety of sugar.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Louisiana Planter and Sugar Manufacturer|volume=55|title=Drying Sugars Essential to Their Preservation|passage=The experience of sugar planters in Louisiana this year in holding their '''sugars''' in warehouse for future sales at better prices has revealed again, as it has done heretofore, the fact that the presence of moisture in the '''sugars''' is inimical to their maintaining their standard of quality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C05KAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22sugars%22&pg=PA180#v=onepage&q=%22sugars%22&f=false|date=September 18 1915}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|chemistry}} Any of various small, water-soluble [[carbohydrate]]s such as are used by [[organism]]s for energy and various other purposes.\n#: {{hyper|en|Thesaurus:carbohydrate}}\n#: {{hypo|en|monosaccharide|disaccharide}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Effects of partial defoliation at transplanting time on subsequent|author=James E. Kraus|year=1942|passage=At the end of the second week there were less reducing '''sugars''' in the unpruned plants than in the previous week, but those in the pruned plants were the same.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hkBa8Wt8HAQC&dq=%22sugars%22&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q=%22sugars%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Nutritional Ecology of the Ruminant|author=Peter J. Van Soest|year=1994|passage=Generally speaking, plants have a much greater variety of '''sugars''' and linkages than animal tissues have.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mwUu6PL1UgC&lpg=PA156&dq=%22sugars%22&pg=PA156#v=onepage&q=%22sugars%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Phytochemical Methods A Guide to Modern Techniques of Plant Analysis|author=A.J. Harborne|year=1998|passage=The major free '''sugars''' in plants are the monosaccharides, glucose and fructose (and the disaccharide sucros), together with traces of xylose, rhamnose and galactose.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vCWHUU6iobwC&lpg=PA236&dq=%22sugars%22&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q=%22sugars%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Plant Surface Microbiology|author=Ajit Varma|year=2007|passage=Although ''H. bertonii'' relies on scale insects to prepare its parasitism site on plants, it directly absorbs and utilizes plant '''sugars'''.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=747-kZT60dcC&lpg=PA159&dq=%22plant%20sugars%22&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q=%22plant%20sugars%22&f=false}}\n# {{lb|en|countable}} A small serving of this substance (typically about one [[teaspoon]]), used to sweeten a drink.\n#: {{ux|en|He usually has his coffee white with one '''sugar'''.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The World To-day: A Monthly Record of Human Progress|volume=30|passage=“A slice of lemon and two '''sugars''', please.” “You needn't have said that. I know how you like your tea. I know how you like everything.”|year=1916|title=Miss Fanny Goes to Great Lengths|author=Cosmo Hamilton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ve1HAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22two%20sugars%20please%22&pg=PA369#v=onepage&q=%22two%20sugars%20please%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|actor=Bill Murray|role=Phil|title=Groundhog Day|year=1993|time=1:13:03|passage=Skim milk, two '''sugar'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Outside the Lines|author=Ameera Patel|year=2016|passage=Then there are the coffees, one with two sweeteners and no milk, one with one sweetener and milk, one with three '''sugars''' and a dash of milk, one with one '''sugar''' and lots of milk and finally her Uncle Samad who says that anything is fine.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F63kCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA39&dq=%22with%20one%20sugar'%22&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q=%22with%20one%20sugar'%22&f=false}}\n# A bowl or other container of sugar.\n#: {{ux|en|Pass the '''sugar''', please}}\n# {{lb|en|countable}} {{non-gloss|A term of endearment.}}\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:sweetheart}}\n#: {{ux|en|I'll be with you in a moment, '''sugar'''.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|text='''Sugar''', ah honey honey / You are my candy girl / And you've got me wanting you|artist=w:The Archies|title=w:Sugar, Sugar|year=1969|album=w:Everything's Archie}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|slang}} [[affection|Affection]] shown by [[kiss|kisses]] or [[kissing]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:buss}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|actor=Bruce Campbell|role=Ash Williams|title=Army of Darkness|year=1992|passage=Gimme some '''sugar''', baby.}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|southern|_|US|slang|uncountable}} [[effeminacy|Effeminacy]] in a male, often implying [[homosexuality]].\n#: {{ux|en|I think John has a little bit of '''sugar''' in him.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1998|title=Sweetness and Strength|author=Lene Østermark-Johansen|ISBN=1859284523|passage=There are depths and heights of beauty in him beyond tears - but there is no '''sugar''', not even any honey.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1999|title=My Husband Wears My Clothes|author=Peggy J. Rudd|ISBN=096267625X|passage=The crossdresser is showing the desire to be \"'''sugar''' and spice\" through feminine clothing and through the expression of feminine feelings. }}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008 |title=Living Through the Hoop|author=Reuben A. Buford May|ISBN=0814757294|passage=Because of Patrick's mannerisms, the players teased him by referring to him as “Sweetness” or saying that he had “'''sugar'''” in his pants. }}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|informal}} [[diabetes|Diabetes]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|title=Researching Cultural Differences in Health|author=Mrs Sheila Hillier; David Kelleher|page=94|ISBN=1134832761|passage=One respondent said that he had been told by his doctor that he had ''''sugar'''' and diabetes, thus affirming for him the distinctiveness of the two illnesses. The distinction made sense to some of them as the relationship between diabetes and ''''sugar'''' seemed to relate to their experiences of the West Indies, where ''''sugar'''' was believed to be rare and diabetes common. }}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|title=Above All We Ask Or Think|author=Tom Lee|page=53|ISBN=1591604249|passage=The veterinarian said his real problem was that he had '''sugar''', and not to concentrate on the problem with his eyes.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004 |title=Reflections on a Life with Diabetes: A Memoir in Many Voices|author=Diane M. Parker; Ruth E. Mark|page=57|ISBN=1589395964|passage=Don't you love it when you start a new Disease - the pamphlets, the prescriptions, the attention? And the past turning ironic, cloudy, as if you'd added a chemical - my house painter saying he has '''sugar''', reminding me of my mother demanding the sweet drool from every baby.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|title=Suppose Jesus Had Thrown in the Towel and Given Up on Us|author=De'lois Washington McMillan |ISBN=1438921063|passage=The doctor told me I had '''sugar''' and would have to take pills.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|title=From Sugar to Splenda|author=Bert Fraser-Reid|ISBN=3642227813|passage=The memorable event was watching my father test urine, his or that of sundry other folks who had “'''sugar'''”, as diabetes was known in the rural hills of Jamaica where I grew up.}}\n# {{lb|en|dated}} Anything resembling sugar in taste or appearance, especially in chemistry.\n#: {{ux|en|'''Sugar''' of lead (lead acetate) is a poisonous white crystalline substance with a sweet taste.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Lives of the French, Italian and German Philosophers|author=M. de Fontenelle|passage=Mons. Lemery is of Opinion that Sweetness proceeds from a close Mixture of an Acid with a Sulphur, or with an Oyl that temperates and corrects it; he supports his Conjecture by the instance of '''Sugar''' of Saturn, so called from its Sweetness, which is Lead, a Metal insipid in its self, but very Sulphureous, dissolved by an Acid.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZGBFAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22sugar%20of%20saturn%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%20of%20saturn%22&f=false|chapter=Upon the Iron of Plants|year=1717}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Physical and chemical essays|author=Torbern Olof Bergman|tlr=E. Cullen|origlang=sv|volume=1|page=448|passage=The fluor acid, the acid of '''sugar''', of phosphorus, and vitriol, separate magnelia from the acid of arsenic; but the acid of tartar, united with arsenicated magnesia, is generally found to compose a triple salt.|chapter=Of Magnesia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxgAAAAAQAAJ&dq=%22sugar%20of%20phosphorus%22&pg=PA448#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%20of%20phosphorus%22&f=false|year=1788}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The American Sugar Industry and Beer Sugar Gazette|volume=6|page=392|year=1904|passage='''Sugar''' of milk is now produced by partly chemical means from milk-whey, the product being about two and a half pounds per hundred pounds of whey.|title=Process of Making Milk Sugar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SeQ7AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22sugar%20of%20milk%22&pg=PA392#v=onepage&q=%22sugar%20of%20milk%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013|title=From Alchemy to Chemistry|author=John Read|url= https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/From_Alchemy_to_Chemistry/_sPDAgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=“vitriol+of+Venus”&pg=PT51&printsec=frontcover|passage=The association of the heavenly bodies with known metals and also with human organs and destinies goes back to ancient Chaldea, the land of astrologers. In Chaucer’s words: ‘The seven bodies eek, lo hear anon. Sol gold is, and Luna silver we declare; Mars yron, Mercurie is quyksilver; Saturnian leed; and Jubitur is tyn, and Venus coper, by my fathers kyn.’ […] Corresponding names were bestowed upon salts of these metals by the alchemists, and some of them have persisted down to the present day. Some examples are lunar caustic (silver nitrate); vitriol of Venus (copper sulphate); '''sugar''' of Saturn (lead acetate); and vitriol of Mars, or Martial vitriol (ferrous sulphate).}}\n# [[compliment|Compliment]] or [[flattery]] used to disguise or render acceptable something obnoxious; honeyed or soothing words.\n# {{lb|en|US|slang|uncountable}} [[heroin|Heroin]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:heroin}}\n# {{lb|en|US|slang|uncountable|dated}} [[money|Money]]. <!--in e.g. Inner Sanctum radio episode \"Death on the Highway\"-->\n# {{lb|en|programming}} {{cap|syntactic sugar}}.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2005|author=Bruce Ian Mills|title=Theoretical Introduction to Programming|page=180|passage=However, this bookkeeping is much less local syntax and '''sugar'''.}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col3|en\n|title=Hyponyms of sugar (noun)|5-nitro-2-propoxyaniline\n|aldose\n|alitame\n|allose\n|altrose\n|aspartame\n|amylose\n|arabinose\n|carbohydrate\n|cellulose\n|cyclamate\n|decose\n|demerara\n|dextrose\n|dulcin\n|erythritol\n|erythrose\n|erythrulose\n|fructose\n|fucose\n|furanose\n|galactose\n|glucose\n|glycyrrhizin\n|gulose\n|heptose\n|hexose\n|idose\n|inulin\n|isomalt\n|ketose\n|lactilol\n|lactose|lump-sugar\n|lyxose\n|maltitol\n|maltose\n|mannitol\n|mannose\n|monellin\n|neohesperidin dihydrochalcone\n|neotame\n|nonose\n|octose\n|pentose\n|polyol\n|psicose\n|pyranose\n|rhamnose\n|ribose\n|ribulose\n|saccharide\n|saccharin\n|sedoheptulose\n|sorbitol\n|sorbose\n|steviol glycoside\n|stachyose\n|sucralose\n|sucrose\n|tagatose\n|talose\n|tetrose\n|thaumatin\n|threose\n|trehalose\n|triose\n|volemitol\n|xylitol\n|xylose\n|xylulose}}\n\n====Meronyms====\n{{col3|en\n|title=Meronyms of sugar (noun)|agave syrup\n|barley malt syrup\n|blanco directo\n|birch syrup\n|brazzein\n|brown rice syrup\n|caramel\n|corn syrup\n|fruit syrup\n|golden syrup\n|goor,gur\n|high fructose corn syrup\n|holing cane\n|honey\n|karupatti\n|jaggery\n|lugduname\n|maple syrup\n|mizuame\n|molasses\n|muscovado\n|panela\n|panocha,panoche\n|rum\n|Steen's cane syrup\n|stevia\n|sweetener\n|sweet sorghum\n|syrup\n|treacle\n|turbinado}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|sugarworks\n|10x sugar|cube sugar|sugar ant|sugar belly|sugar bro|sugar cone\n|acid of sugar\n|acorn sugar\n|ambered sugar\n|amino sugar,aminosugar\n|anhydrosugar\n|anhydrous sugar\n|animal sugar\n|aphis-sugar\n|as sweet as sugar\n|baker's sugar\n|Barbados sugar\n|barley sugar,barley-sugar|sugar and spice and everything nice\n|bar sugar\n|bastard sugar\n|beechwood sugar|sugar dating\n|beetroot sugar\n|beet sugar,beet-sugar\n|berry sugar\n|besugar\n|birch sugar\n|black sugar\n|blanch sugar\n|blood sugar\n|brain sugar| Schardinger sugar\n|blown sugar|pulverized sugar\n|boiled sugar\n|brown sugar|magic sugar|sugar down|sugar nips|sugar up\n|burnt sugar\n|candied sugar|antisugar|arsenosugar|azasugar|azidosugar|bromosugar|chitosugar|chlorosugar|deoxysugar|dideoxysugar|fluorosugar|galactosugar|halosugar|iminosugar|iodosugar|liposugar|monosugar|multisugar|oligosugar|polysugar|pseudosugar|sugarcoated|sugarcraft|sugarfree|sugarful|sugarholic|sugarlike|sugarmaker|sugarmaking|sugarman|sugarpie|sugarstick|sugartits\n|candy sugar\n|cane sugar,cane-sugar\n|caramelised sugar,caramelized sugar\n|caramel sugar\n|caster sugar,castor sugar\n|CDP-sugar\n|centrifugal sugar\n|cinnamon sugar\n|clarified sugar\n|clayed sugar\n|coarse sugar\n|coffee sugar\n|colored sugar crystals\n|compound sugar\n|compressible sugar\n|confectioner's sugar,confectioners' sugar\n|corn sugar\n|corn sugar syrup\n|cracked sugar\n|crashed sugar\n|crude sugar\n|crushed sugar\n|crystalline sugar|fasting blood sugar|sugar louse\n|crystallisable sugar,crystallizable sugar\n|crystallised sugar,crystallized sugar\n|crystal sugar\n|culinary sugar\n|cytidine diphosphosugar\n|date sugar,date-sugar\n|dehydrosugar\n|demerara sugar\n|deoxy sugar,desoxy sugar\n|desugar<!--computing term?-->\n|